title: For Sale:  FN SCAR 17S Assault Rifle. 308 FDE New In Box
postcontent:
It is a well-built rifle, very reliable, easy to shoot, and match-accurate. The FN SCAR is the semi- automatic civilian version of the short-stroke gas piston rifle issued to the Army Ranger's of U.S. Special Operations Command.
The FN SCAR's barrel is free-floating within the hand guard. The buttstock is adjustable for length-of-pull, and also folds to the right side for easier transport or use in confined quarters. The buttstock locks onto the empty case deflector when folded. There are numerous sling attachment points on the 17s. The FN SCAR 17s grip is of AR-10 style, as is the bolt release lever and the magazine release button.

The FN SCAR has folding sights that are fully adjustable for windage and elevation correction, with dual apertures at the rear, and is marked for distance on the elevation adjustment. The comb height is adjustable for easier use with optical sights. The FN SCAR 17s has a reciprocating bolt handle that can be switched to either side, and it also serves as a forward assist. The magazine release is ambidextrous and the muzzle is fitted for a threaded PWS muzzle brake. The gas regulator has two working positions, plus a disassembly position. The normal position is for unsuppressed use, and the second operable position is for use with a sound suppressor.

title: For Sale:  5 Bushmaster AR-15 magazines, New In Wrapper
postcontent:
5 Bushmaster 30-round magazines
$150 for all 5 -- that's $30 each.

I will not break up the set, since it would not be worth my time and effort to sell these separately.

These are still in the wrapper. 


8448670R
BSH MAGAZINE 223 30RD

is printed on the wrapper labels.


The magazines are marked

RESTRICTED MILITARY
GOV'T / LAW ENFORCEMENT
EXPORT USE ONLY

along with the date of manufacture

"4 04" on 1 of the magazines, and
"6 04" on 4 of the magazines,

as was required by law during the Assault Weapons Ban (AWB) of 1994 - 2004.  Since that ban expired in September 2004, these have been legal to own.


Bushmasters is/was selling these for $22.00 each -- see http://www.bushmaster.com/products.asp?cat=9  and scroll down -- but of course they are currently out-of-stock.





Please really think about whether or not you want to pay this much for AR-15 magazines.

As we are all painfully aware, the price of AR-15 magazines has skyrocketed to ridiculous levels in the past several weeks, due to the threat of future restrictions.

If no legislation passes (and there is no hyper-inflation), you will be able to buy brand new military spec and P-Mag AR-15 magazines for $10 to $20 each -- and overpriced FN and HK brand mags for $30 to $50 each -- within a few months.  And the market will be so flooded with used magazines that they should be almost free.

If I believed that AR-15 magazines will not be available in the future, I would not be selling these.  If, however, somebody wants to pay inflated prices for AR-15 magazines, I can spare a few from my personal stash to finance some other projects.  When the market returns to normal I'll just buy some more.

The sad truth is that if you buy these magazines from me at this price, it means that one of us is going to be wrong about the future and will regret it.

Anderson Manufacturing, a machine shop that rescued its operations by entering the business of designing and manufacturing AR-15 style rifles, now offers five different models of rifles for hunting, target shooting, and military/police applications.

Designated with the “AM” (Anderson Manufacturing) moniker to set them apart from traditional “AR” (Armalite Rifle) models, Anderson Manufacturing rifles offer design and build quality that exceeds that of other firearms manufacturers around the world along with RF-85, a proprietary metal treatment.

Anderson Manufacturing employs a proprietary metal treatment for all its rifles that reduces friction on all the steel surfaces by 85%, resulting in a more efficient and reliable weapon. The ArmaLite AR50 made the trip from my apartment to my trunk wrapped in a green wool blanket as I nodded nonchalantly to my neighbors."
...
"The AmraLite AR50′s action is butter smooth. There’s no magazine on the gun and therefore no follower to get in the way. Cycling the bolt is effortless. Even after 60 rounds of dirty machine gun grade ammo the bolt moved back and forth with ease. Closing the bolt is a little stiff, but not much worse than a standard Mosin action."
...
"The AR-50 was designed to do one thing and do it well: hit targets at extreme ranges. According to their 1999 press release, the rifle is an ' . . . economical, accurate rifle for shooters interested in the challenges of long range shooting.' And that’s all it does. It’s a highly specialized piece of equipment with limited use. But where it’s useful, it’s perfect. It’s precisely the right tool for the job: punching precision holes in far away targets."  |-----
